The XPS spectra of cellulose, CHIS before and after adsorption of Cr(VI) and Hg(II) ions is shown in Fig. 6 . The spectra of CHIS exhibited peaks of carbon, oxygen and nitrogen (Fig. 6(m)), while CHIS complexed with Hg(II) (Fig. 6(n)), the spectra also revealed two additional sharp peaks at 100.9 eV and 104.9 eV for Hg(II) (Fig. 6(l)), corresponding to 4f7/2 and 4f5/2, with slight shift and increase in intensity of peaks of carbon, oxygen and nitrogen (Singh et al., 2012). The Cr(VI) CHIS complex (Fig. 6(k)) shows two intense peaks at 575.99 eV and 586.14 eV (Fig. 6(o)) corresponding to Cr3+ (2P3/2) and Cr3+(2P1/2), respectively, whereas two shoulder peaks at 578.3 eV and 587.8 eV correspond to Cr6+(2P1/2) and Cr6+(2P1/2), respectively. Additional peaks were also observed on treatment with chromate ions with slight alteration in peak intensity and shift in binding energy of carbon, nitrogen and oxygen based functional group. The C1s region of the XPS spectrum of CHIS (Fig. 6(a)) shows highest peaks at 284.8 eV corresponding to C–H and peak at 286.2 eV corresponding to CN bond and a shoulder peak at 287.6 eV representing C–N bond (
Xi et al., 2020
). On addition of Hg(II) (Fig. 6(d)), suppression of all the three peaks were observed, however the sharp peak at 284.8 eV in CHIS suppressed more as compared to peak at 286.2 eV. Both C–H and CN peak shows slight shift in peak of about 0.26 eV on addition of Hg(II) ions. In case of Cr(VI) ions, C–H peak got inhibited more as compared Hg(II) ions, while CN peak intensity increased slightly, whereas the shoulder peak in case of CHIS matured to be a peak with slight rise in intensity (Fig. 6(g)). On addition of Cr(VI) C–H peaks showed 0.26 eV shift but no shift in peak observed in CN peak which implies interaction of Cr(VI) ions occurs majorly through C–H bond. The N1s spectra of CHIS (Fig. 6(b)) can be deconvoluted into four major peaks, corresponding sp2 CN bond (397.5 eV), N–H (398.9 eV), CN–C (398.2 eV), pyrrolic nitrogen C–NH–C (400.0 eV) and a peak at 399.5 eV because of presence of aromatic nitrogen of imidazole ring which also confirms nitrogen containing L-histidine successfully grafted on cellulose (Jang et al., 2009). On the adsorption of Hg(II) ions (Fig. 6(e)), all the peaks get suppressed with highest suppression of peak of nitrogen atom of imidazole ring at 399.5 eV, which confirms the fact that Hg(II) ions interact with CHIS through the nitrogen atom of imine group. On the adsorption of Cr(VI) ions, CHIS shows lower suppression of peak as compared to Hg(II) ions, almost similar suppression of peaks at 399.5 eV, N–H (398.9 eV), CN–C (398.2 eV) and N–H peaks at 400.03 eV, 400.8 eV, C–NH–C (401.4 eV) (Fig. 6(h)). This implies that initially, electrostatic interactions between chromate ion and CHIS with equal affinity of chromate ion for CN and N–H group of L-histidine. The O1s spectra of CHIS (Fig. 6(c)) can be deconvoluted into two peaks at 532.8 eV corresponding to C–O and a shoulder peak at 531 eV, corresponding to CO bond (Shen et al., 2013). Peak corresponding to C–O at 531 eV and 532.8 eV showed enhancement on addition of Hg(II) ions (Fig. 6(f)). On the other hand, additions of Cr(VI) ions to CHIS adsorbent caused enhancement in both the peaks, and 0.3eV shift in binding energy to 532.5 eV which supports electrostatic and hydrogen bonding interaction between chromate ion and C–O group and CO group, of CHIS (Fig. 6(i)). Absence in enhancement of shoulder peak of CO also indicate lower interaction of CHIS with Hg(II) metal ion, corroborating the suggested mechanism in the previous section.
